<section xml:id="TRIGONOMETRY">
  <title>TRIGONOMETRY</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Right-angled triangles have specific trigonometric properties, which can be used to find unknown dimensions or angles.
      A side can be <em>opposite</em> to one angle and <em>adjacent</em> to a different angle.
      <term>The location of the angle determines the relationships “opposite” or “adjacent”.</term>
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="definitions-soh-cah-toa">
    <title>Basic Definitions (SOH-CAH-TOA)</title>

    <list>
      <title>
        The three primary trigonometric ratios are:
      </title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\sin \theta = \frac{\text{Opposite}}{\text{Hypotenuse}}</m> (SOH)
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\cos \theta = \frac{\text{Adjacent}}{\text{Hypotenuse}}</m> (CAH)
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\tan \theta = \frac{\text{Opposite}}{\text{Adjacent}}</m> (TOA)
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </list>
  </subsection>

